at the festival.

00:01:14.130 --> 00:01:15.470
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: this is amazing.

00:01:15.470 --> 00:01:17.560
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN:
And to have you.

00:01:17.560 --> 00:01:22.200
And I have a bio, I think
when they talk about a person

00:01:22.200 --> 00:01:27.530
who needs no introduction,
you might be that person.

00:01:27.530 --> 00:01:33.020
But I would like to read just a
little bit, if you don't mind.

00:01:33.020 --> 00:01:34.320
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: I don't mind.

00:01:34.320 --> 00:01:35.620
CHP: How about it?

00:01:35.620 --> 00:01:36.920
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: They might mind.

00:01:36.920 --> 00:01:41.390
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: Well, Justice
Sotomayor is an associate

00:01:41.390 --> 00:01:44.550
justice of the US Supreme Court
and she was born in the Bronx.

00:01:44.550 --> 00:01:54.330
Well. [Audience] She earned a
BA from Princeton University

00:01:54.330 --> 00:01:58.060
and a JD -- oh, little
applause, little applause.

00:01:58.060 --> 00:02:01.910
And a JD from Yale Law school.

00:02:01.910 --> 00:02:07.460
And in 1991 President George
H. W. Bush nominated her

00:02:07.460 --> 00:02:11.190
to the US District Court,
Southern District of New York.

00:02:11.190 --> 00:02:17.300
In 1997, President Bill Clinton
nominated her to the US Court

00:02:17.300 --> 00:02:19.800
of Appeals for the
Second Circuit.

00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:23.030
And then President
Barrack Obama nominated her

00:02:23.030 --> 00:02:24.830
to the Supreme Court.

00:02:24.830 --> 00:02:33.600
[ Applause ]

00:02:33.600 --> 00:02:40.940
On May 26, 2009, and she was
confirmed on August the 8, 2009.

00:02:40.940 --> 00:02:44.510
Becoming the first
Latina on the high court.

00:02:44.510 --> 00:02:52.360
[ Applause ]

00:02:52.360 --> 00:02:54.680
And she's a bestselling author.

00:02:54.680 --> 00:02:58.210
"My Beloved World,"
among others.

00:02:58.210 --> 00:03:03.720
However, Justice, you have
done something remarkable,

00:03:03.720 --> 00:03:05.280
a first for the book festival.

00:03:05.280 --> 00:03:06.580
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR:

00:03:06.580 --> 00:03:09.030
And how many years has
this been going on now?

00:03:09.030 --> 00:03:10.410
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: 18 years.

00:03:10.410 --> 00:03:11.950
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR:
That's a long time.

00:03:11.950 --> 00:03:15.010
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: In 18
years we've never had

00:03:15.010 --> 00:03:22.650
on the main stage books that
were written for young people.

00:03:22.650 --> 00:03:27.790
But because of you and --

00:03:27.790 --> 00:03:31.910
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR:
Carla, kids are powerful.

00:03:31.910 --> 00:03:34.880
They are.

00:03:34.880 --> 00:03:36.610
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: I
know, but it took you

00:03:36.610 --> 00:03:39.780
to get us on the main stage.

00:03:39.780 --> 00:03:42.160
And, so that really
intrigued me,

00:03:42.160 --> 00:03:46.230
because I'm a former
children's librarian and we know

00:03:46.230 --> 00:03:48.560
about the power of books,
but what motivated you?

00:03:48.560 --> 00:03:52.830
With all the things that you
could do and people asking you

00:03:52.830 --> 00:03:56.790
to write other books,
why would you write

00:03:56.790 --> 00:03:58.680
for young people, what was it?

00:03:58.680 --> 00:04:00.780
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: Well, with respect

00:04:00.780 --> 00:04:04.150
to the middle school
book, "The Beloved World

00:04:04.150 --> 00:04:10.130
of Sonia Sotomayor," kids you're
going to meet my cousin Miriam.

00:04:10.130 --> 00:04:12.880
She's six months
younger than I am

00:04:12.880 --> 00:04:17.000
and I tortured her always
telling her I was older.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:21.700
Now we're older and she tortures
me telling me I'm younger.

00:04:22.920 --> 00:04:28.570
But, she's a middle school
bilingual education teacher.

00:04:28.570 --> 00:04:35.250
And when I wrote my parent
book, "My Beloved World,"

00:04:35.250 --> 00:04:36.950
she asked me immediately

00:04:36.950 --> 00:04:39.990
to start writing a
middle school book.

00:04:39.990 --> 00:04:42.290
But, you know, I have a day job.

00:04:44.850 --> 00:04:49.150
And sometimes I'm very very busy
and it took me a number of years

00:04:49.150 --> 00:04:52.960
to try to make the
time to write this.

00:04:52.960 --> 00:04:55.630
So, I decided to write
this, as I was thinking

00:04:55.630 --> 00:05:02.540
about writing it I thought, "But
really, how about young readers,

00:05:02.540 --> 00:05:06.410
this may not quite be
appropriate for them yet."

00:05:06.410 --> 00:05:09.210
So, if I'm going to do
one I should do the other,

00:05:09.210 --> 00:05:11.130
shouldn't i?

00:05:11.130 --> 00:05:15.120
And then I thought,
"It's a real challenge,

00:05:15.120 --> 00:05:19.640
how do I tell my story
to young readers in a way

00:05:19.640 --> 00:05:22.750
that they can understand
in words,

00:05:22.750 --> 00:05:25.550
but that they could
see as well?"

00:05:25.550 --> 00:05:31.700
So, I thought about it and I
said, "Ah, an illustrated book."

00:05:31.700 --> 00:05:39.910
And then I had the pure
fortuity to find an illustrator,

00:05:39.910 --> 00:05:47.450
Lulu Delacre, who could
turn my story into pictures.

00:05:47.450 --> 00:05:50.110
And beautiful pictures.

00:05:50.110 --> 00:05:53.270
And, so, "Turning
Pages," was born.

00:05:53.270 --> 00:06:00.110
And that's me walking up the
steps of the Supreme Court.

00:06:00.110 --> 00:06:02.440
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: I
understand she's here.

00:06:02.440 --> 00:06:04.810
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR:
That's me with the high heels.

00:06:04.810 --> 00:06:08.070
Not today.

00:06:08.070 --> 00:06:10.270
But I have worn high heels.

00:06:10.270 --> 00:06:13.250
I like them.

00:06:13.250 --> 00:06:17.350
And there's a little
frog, the Coqui,

00:06:17.350 --> 00:06:19.510
which is a symbol
of Puerto Rico.

00:06:19.510 --> 00:06:25.240
[ Applause ]

00:06:25.240 --> 00:06:30.140
And in my hands there's a key.

00:06:30.140 --> 00:06:33.380
And that's what this
book is about,

00:06:33.380 --> 00:06:37.720
the key to success in my life.

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:43.340
It's the secret that I
want to share with kids.

00:06:43.340 --> 00:06:48.750
It tells and explains this
book how I became successful.

00:06:48.750 --> 00:06:54.390
And what's the answer -- I
could tell you to read the book.

00:06:55.600 --> 00:06:58.160
I hope you will anyway.

00:06:58.160 --> 00:07:01.190
But what I know is that I'm here

00:07:01.190 --> 00:07:06.360
as a Supreme Court Justice
only because of books.

00:07:06.360 --> 00:07:08.510
Because reading books

00:07:08.510 --> 00:07:16.040
[ Applause ]

00:07:16.040 --> 00:07:18.210
Opened the world to me.

00:07:18.210 --> 00:07:19.990
So, that's what this is about.

00:07:19.990 --> 00:07:22.350
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: And, Justice,
and I'm going to tell everybody,

00:07:22.350 --> 00:07:28.800
I don't get to endorse books
much now or anything like that,

00:07:28.800 --> 00:07:32.800
but let's just say,
I love this book.

00:07:32.800 --> 00:07:36.520
I got an advance copy,
that's one of the perks.

00:07:36.520 --> 00:07:40.200
And I couldn't -- it
was just so evocative

00:07:40.200 --> 00:07:43.110
of what the power
of reading can do.

00:07:43.110 --> 00:07:45.990
You started with
your grandmother

00:07:45.990 --> 00:07:48.980
and I had a grandmother that
read to me or did words,

00:07:48.980 --> 00:07:50.280
and tell us about that.

00:07:50.280 --> 00:07:53.460
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR:
Well, I'm going to start

00:07:53.460 --> 00:07:57.820
by telling you that probably
the most important person

00:07:57.820 --> 00:08:02.100
in my life was my
abuelita, my grandmother.

00:08:02.100 --> 00:08:06.590
When I started writing
my parent book,

00:08:06.590 --> 00:08:10.960
it was because one day during
the confirmation process my

00:08:10.960 --> 00:08:16.320
mother turned to me and
said, "Sonia, they forgotten

00:08:16.320 --> 00:08:17.920
about Midseres [assumed
spelling].

00:08:17.920 --> 00:08:20.710
That was my abuelita's name.

00:08:20.710 --> 00:08:24.580
And I said, "I know, mom,
because thankfully you're here

00:08:24.580 --> 00:08:27.900
with me and you've been
so important in my life,

00:08:27.900 --> 00:08:29.330
but I will find a way

00:08:29.330 --> 00:08:32.420
that everybody will
know about abuelita."

00:08:32.420 --> 00:08:36.560
And my way was to put
her into my adult book.

00:08:36.560 --> 00:08:40.190
So, I then created
this children's book

00:08:40.190 --> 00:08:45.340
and I include a picture of her
at my high school graduation.

00:08:45.340 --> 00:08:48.080
And, so, that's my abuelita.

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:56.130
And the first scene that
you see in "Turning Pages,"

00:08:56.130 --> 00:09:01.570
is me walking with her,
going on Saturday morning

00:09:01.570 --> 00:09:05.930
to buy a chicken for
dinner Saturday night.

00:09:05.930 --> 00:09:10.340
So, she's very much a part
of this book, and in fact,

00:09:10.340 --> 00:09:16.090
I dedicated this book to her, my
mother and the role model women

00:09:16.090 --> 00:09:21.320
in my life, because they
have really set the stage

00:09:21.320 --> 00:09:22.620
for who I became.

00:09:22.620 --> 00:09:25.340
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: And
then you talked about --

00:09:25.340 --> 00:09:29.320
sorry, but I know this
book by heart now.

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:36.130
And librarians and teachers
and anyone that believes

00:09:36.130 --> 00:09:39.180
in the power of books and
reading and literacy is going

00:09:39.180 --> 00:09:41.700
to get so much, because you
talk about seeing yourself

00:09:41.700 --> 00:09:43.950
or not seeing yourself in books.

00:09:43.950 --> 00:09:49.930
Books were a lifeline for you
and you need to see yourself.

00:09:49.930 --> 00:09:53.160
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR:
books, you know, most of us,

00:09:53.160 --> 00:09:56.740
not all of us, but most of
us, and especially those of us

00:09:56.740 --> 00:10:01.110
who come from modest
backgrounds, we don't get

00:10:01.110 --> 00:10:05.700
to see much of the world when
we're growing up as kids.

00:10:05.700 --> 00:10:10.430
We all -- anyway, tend to live
within a few blocks of our home.

00:10:10.430 --> 00:10:14.180
That's where we usually play,
most of our friends are there,

00:10:14.180 --> 00:10:17.280
unless you live in big cities
like New York, and everybody has

00:10:17.280 --> 00:10:19.620
to travel when they're
in New York.

00:10:19.620 --> 00:10:24.400
But for most people
your world is very small

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:27.100
or at least the world
that you inhabit.

00:10:27.100 --> 00:10:29.720
The bigger world is
something you have to explore

00:10:29.720 --> 00:10:33.520
with time and age often.

00:10:33.520 --> 00:10:36.220
And, so, books give
you a chance to do

00:10:36.220 --> 00:10:40.080
that in a way nothing else does.

00:10:40.080 --> 00:10:44.050
You see, television and
movies, and even the internet,

00:10:44.050 --> 00:10:46.840
they present you with pictures,

00:10:46.840 --> 00:10:51.230
but what they don't
let you do is imagine.

00:10:51.230 --> 00:10:57.580
The power of words is in
creating pictures in your mind

00:10:57.580 --> 00:11:03.420
and when you can do that
without television or movies

00:11:03.420 --> 00:11:07.180
or real pictures telling
you what you should imagine,

00:11:07.180 --> 00:11:09.910
it can become more special.

00:11:09.910 --> 00:11:15.900
And, so, for me I explored the
world as a child through books

00:11:15.900 --> 00:11:19.260
and I saw the possibilities
of things

00:11:19.260 --> 00:11:22.690
that I never could have
imagined without reading.

00:11:22.690 --> 00:11:28.590
I could never have imagined
traveling to faraway places.

00:11:28.590 --> 00:11:32.860
And now I do it, but it
was that wish to do it,

00:11:32.860 --> 00:11:37.350
that lust to meet other people
in the world, came from reading

00:11:37.350 --> 00:11:42.290
about where other people
lived and wanting to see it.

00:11:42.290 --> 00:11:45.160
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: What
about the thinking

00:11:45.160 --> 00:11:47.970
about a legal profession or law

00:11:47.970 --> 00:11:51.240
and how reading helped
you get into that?

00:11:51.240 --> 00:11:52.700
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: Well, mothers

00:11:52.700 --> 00:11:55.950
and fathers are not
going to like this.

00:11:55.950 --> 00:11:57.250
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: Uht oh.

00:11:57.250 --> 00:11:58.550
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: Look,

00:11:58.550 --> 00:12:00.450
in my life there
were no lawyers.

00:12:00.450 --> 00:12:06.500
I grew up in a housing project,
which is a place where people

00:12:06.500 --> 00:12:08.430
without resources,

00:12:08.430 --> 00:12:11.740
the government helps
them find housing.

00:12:11.740 --> 00:12:15.730
And, so, there were no
lawyers in the projects.

00:12:15.730 --> 00:12:19.750
And there were no lawyers
anywhere in my life.

00:12:19.750 --> 00:12:22.680
And, so, I had no
opportunities to know

00:12:22.680 --> 00:12:26.810
about really the law,
except in a bad way.

00:12:26.810 --> 00:12:28.900
A lot of my cousins and a lot

00:12:28.900 --> 00:12:32.370
of people I knew got
arrested by the police.

00:12:32.370 --> 00:12:36.540
Andi knew they went to court
and it was very painful

00:12:36.540 --> 00:12:39.330
for our families and friends.

00:12:39.330 --> 00:12:45.700
But that's not a good sort of
image of what law is all about.

00:12:45.700 --> 00:12:50.460
However, through television
I found a TV lawyer,

00:12:50.460 --> 00:12:53.510
the first one, Perry Mason.

00:12:53.510 --> 00:13:00.630
[ Applause ]

00:13:00.630 --> 00:13:05.960
And he showed me that
lawyers could help people.

00:13:05.960 --> 00:13:11.520
And, so, my first childhood
understanding of lawyers

00:13:11.520 --> 00:13:15.760
and law was that
they help people.

00:13:15.760 --> 00:13:21.100
And that seemed like a really
good thing for me to do.

00:13:21.100 --> 00:13:25.260
But it took a lot longer,
my getting a little older,

00:13:25.260 --> 00:13:29.260
going to college and doing
other things to realize

00:13:29.260 --> 00:13:35.910
that what law helps
people do is live together.

00:13:35.910 --> 00:13:40.520
You see, laws help our
relationships with one another.

00:13:40.520 --> 00:13:45.410
The laws tell us certain
limits of what we can do with

00:13:45.410 --> 00:13:48.380
and to and for each other.

00:13:48.380 --> 00:13:53.900
Laws are not morality,
they're not right and wrong,

00:13:53.900 --> 00:13:57.510
they are a way of
regulating our relationships

00:13:57.510 --> 00:14:01.430
so we can manage our
competing interests.

00:14:01.430 --> 00:14:05.230
You know? When your
mother tells you,

00:14:05.230 --> 00:14:10.170
"You can't borrow your
brother or sister's toys

00:14:10.170 --> 00:14:13.630
without asking them
for permission."

00:14:13.630 --> 00:14:17.460
That's the first seed of
teaching you what laws do.

00:14:17.460 --> 00:14:20.420
You can't steal other
people's property.

00:14:20.420 --> 00:14:25.580
You can't take that without
them saying it's okay.

00:14:25.580 --> 00:14:30.200
That is regulating
our competing interest

00:14:30.200 --> 00:14:34.060
and telling us how we
can live better together.

00:14:34.060 --> 00:14:36.450
And I wanted to be
a part of that.

00:14:36.450 --> 00:14:42.850
I wanted to be a part or a voice
in how we live with each other.

00:14:42.850 --> 00:14:50.140
And that became my reality
by reading about what law did

00:14:50.140 --> 00:14:54.470
and does and the good
it's done in society.

00:14:54.470 --> 00:14:58.600
You know, I was born
on May 25, 1954,

00:14:58.600 --> 00:15:02.570
one month before a very
important Supreme Court case was

00:15:02.570 --> 00:15:07.510
decided, Brown versus
Board of Education.

00:15:07.510 --> 00:15:12.040
[ Applause ]

00:15:12.040 --> 00:15:17.220
We are sitting in this room,
one collection of people

00:15:17.220 --> 00:15:21.060
of all races, of all
backgrounds, of all --

00:15:21.060 --> 00:15:24.470
of both genders,
because of Brown.

00:15:24.470 --> 00:15:28.520
Before this our society
was segregated.

00:15:28.520 --> 00:15:33.050
And segregated right here
in the nation's capital.

00:15:33.050 --> 00:15:36.620
When I was born I have
friends who tell me stories

00:15:36.620 --> 00:15:41.330
of traveling south to
Florida, getting on the train

00:15:41.330 --> 00:15:46.030
and stopping in Washington
DC and having to go

00:15:46.030 --> 00:15:48.790
into a segregated car.

00:15:48.790 --> 00:15:53.940
Brown changed my life and all
of our lives for the better.

00:15:53.940 --> 00:15:57.830
Now, there are some laws
that are not very good.

00:15:59.220 --> 00:16:02.620
They're not good because
you don't like them, right?

00:16:02.620 --> 00:16:04.990
You can find one, I'm sure.

00:16:06.070 --> 00:16:09.490
But, laws are made by people

00:16:09.490 --> 00:16:13.320
and we can change laws
that we don't like.

00:16:13.320 --> 00:16:16.490
And we can work hard to do that.

00:16:18.030 --> 00:16:20.820
[applause] The point is that
the law can't get it right all

00:16:20.820 --> 00:16:22.580
of the time.

00:16:22.580 --> 00:16:27.660
Some very good laws are passed
and as society changes they have

00:16:27.660 --> 00:16:29.520
to be amended or altered,

00:16:29.520 --> 00:16:33.520
because they're not doing what
people thought they would do.

00:16:33.520 --> 00:16:37.730
And sometimes the society
sits back and says,

00:16:37.730 --> 00:16:40.970
"There are some things that
are not constitutional,

00:16:40.970 --> 00:16:45.470
like segregation and we
have to change that."

00:16:45.470 --> 00:16:53.250
And, so, for me, books again
were the key to my deciding

00:16:53.250 --> 00:16:55.980
to become what I am today.

00:16:55.980 --> 00:17:00.960
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: Now, you also
though, liked comic books.

00:17:00.960 --> 00:17:02.800
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: Oh, yeah.

00:17:02.800 --> 00:17:06.610
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: And you
wanted to be a superhero.

00:17:06.610 --> 00:17:07.910
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: Oh, yeah.

00:17:07.910 --> 00:17:09.210
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: See,
that's in here too.

00:17:09.210 --> 00:17:10.510
And Nancy Drew.

00:17:10.510 --> 00:17:11.810
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR:
Can I show that picture?

00:17:11.810 --> 00:17:13.110
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: Oh, yeah,
show them that picture.

00:17:13.110 --> 00:17:14.410
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: All right.

00:17:14.410 --> 00:17:15.710
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: And Nancy Drew.

00:17:15.710 --> 00:17:19.500
Shout out to Nancy Drew.

00:17:19.500 --> 00:17:22.100
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: Hold on.

00:17:22.100 --> 00:17:29.150
That's me when I was
diagnosed with diabetes.

00:17:29.150 --> 00:17:30.510
Can I read that passage to them?

00:17:30.510 --> 00:17:31.810
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: Sure,

00:17:31.810 --> 00:17:33.810
the beauty of the words
tell about this story.

00:17:33.810 --> 00:17:36.550
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR:
When I was 7 I got sick

00:17:36.550 --> 00:17:39.650
and was diagnosed with diabetes.

00:17:39.650 --> 00:17:43.460
I was so afraid of the big
needle used to take my blood

00:17:43.460 --> 00:17:47.420
for testing at the
hospital, that I ran outside

00:17:47.420 --> 00:17:50.320
and hid under a parked car.

00:17:50.320 --> 00:17:52.620
That's me under the car.

00:17:54.780 --> 00:17:58.650
I would have to get shots
every day to stay alive.

00:17:58.650 --> 00:18:02.420
All those needles were scary.

00:18:02.420 --> 00:18:08.730
I found my courage in an
unlikely place, comic books.

00:18:08.730 --> 00:18:11.340
After reading stories
of regular people

00:18:11.340 --> 00:18:16.110
who had secret super powers
that could save the world,

00:18:16.110 --> 00:18:21.190
I imagined being as brave
and powerful as they were.

00:18:21.190 --> 00:18:24.510
Then I learned how to
give myself the shots

00:18:24.510 --> 00:18:27.670
and in time I got used to it.

00:18:27.670 --> 00:18:32.030
Books that seemed were magic
potions that could fuel me

00:18:32.030 --> 00:18:35.790
with the bravery of superheroes.

00:18:35.790 --> 00:18:39.510
So, me as Supergirl.

00:18:39.510 --> 00:18:47.360
[ Applause ]

00:18:47.360 --> 00:18:51.670
Lulu did such an incredible
job on every scene,

00:18:51.670 --> 00:18:54.790
but yes, even comic books.

00:18:54.790 --> 00:18:59.040
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: And I think
that she's here, Lulu is here.

00:18:59.040 --> 00:19:00.340
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: Lulu DeLacre.

00:19:00.340 --> 00:19:02.140
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: Oh,
would you please stand up.

00:19:02.140 --> 00:19:12.540
[ Applause ]

00:19:12.540 --> 00:19:16.230
And for Nancy Drew fans,
you really were evocative

00:19:16.230 --> 00:19:18.620
of Nancy Drew during them.

00:19:18.620 --> 00:19:19.920
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR: Now,

00:19:19.920 --> 00:19:21.410
there were no annex
in my life back then.

00:19:21.410 --> 00:19:23.910
I lived in a project and then

00:19:23.910 --> 00:19:27.540
in a big building
complex later in life.

00:19:27.540 --> 00:19:30.600
I've only lived in a house once.

00:19:30.600 --> 00:19:37.690
And that house creaked
all the time and it came

00:19:37.690 --> 00:19:42.330
from the roof -- not the roof,
but the ceiling of the house

00:19:42.330 --> 00:19:46.150
and I really thought that my
friend was keeping something --

00:19:46.150 --> 00:19:49.360
someone prisoner in the attic.

00:19:49.360 --> 00:19:52.950
It took ages before I admitted
this to her and she took me

00:19:52.950 --> 00:19:56.980
up there and said, "No, Sonia,
there's no people up there,

00:19:56.980 --> 00:19:59.790
it's only because it's
a tin roof and it sounds

00:19:59.790 --> 00:20:02.140
like there's footsteps
up there."

00:20:02.140 --> 00:20:05.860
But Lulu put me in a staircase,

00:20:05.860 --> 00:20:08.840
which was much more
familiar to me.

00:20:08.840 --> 00:20:11.320
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: She also
showed you being delighted

00:20:11.320 --> 00:20:15.640
with the delivery of a
box of encyclopedias.

00:20:15.640 --> 00:20:16.940
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR:

00:20:16.940 --> 00:20:18.580
The most beautiful
thing in the world.

00:20:18.580 --> 00:20:21.760
Now, the encyclopedias
today are online,

00:20:21.760 --> 00:20:24.270
they're not selling
them as books anymore.

00:20:24.270 --> 00:20:27.520
And I actually know
there's some value sometimes

00:20:27.520 --> 00:20:29.230
to online reading.

00:20:29.230 --> 00:20:33.140
Those encyclopedias,
if you click on them,

00:20:33.140 --> 00:20:36.430
on something they're
describing, they do a sort

00:20:36.430 --> 00:20:40.790
of 3D image and move it around.

00:20:40.790 --> 00:20:43.100
And that's pretty
interesting I think.

00:20:43.100 --> 00:20:47.110
And I kind of like it, but
I love the encyclopedias.

00:20:47.110 --> 00:20:51.210
The things I could feel in
my hands and turn the pages.

00:20:51.210 --> 00:20:55.090
I actually believe that
if I read every book,

00:20:55.090 --> 00:20:59.220
that I would be the
smartest person in the world.

00:20:59.220 --> 00:21:03.040
Well, it didn't quite work
that way, but I did try

00:21:03.040 --> 00:21:05.640
to read every book and I
got through most of them.

00:21:05.640 --> 00:21:09.460
I didn't understand a
lot of them, but I tried.

00:21:09.460 --> 00:21:14.230
And they introduced me to things
that were very important later.

00:21:14.230 --> 00:21:18.470
When I got to college and I
was taking courses on things

00:21:18.470 --> 00:21:23.170
that were new to me, I might
have read something about it

00:21:23.170 --> 00:21:26.590
in an encyclopedia and it
made me feel a little more

00:21:26.590 --> 00:21:30.830
comfortable that I could
learn more in college.

00:21:30.830 --> 00:21:32.130
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN:
Do you get a chance

00:21:32.130 --> 00:21:35.130
to read anything
for pleasure now?

00:21:35.130 --> 00:21:36.430
I know --

00:21:36.430 --> 00:21:38.110
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: Hardly not.

00:21:38.110 --> 00:21:43.930
I get to a little bit,
so, I was in Canada

00:21:43.930 --> 00:21:46.300
on vacation for a week.

00:21:46.300 --> 00:21:51.080
And -- some nice
Canadians in here, right?

00:21:52.450 --> 00:21:56.480
Anyway, they told me that
the former Chief Justice

00:21:56.480 --> 00:22:02.310
of the Canadian Supreme Court
had written a crime thriller.

00:22:02.310 --> 00:22:04.610
So, I read that.

00:22:05.660 --> 00:22:06.960
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: An escape.

00:22:06.960 --> 00:22:08.260
Still a story.

00:22:08.260 --> 00:22:09.800
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: it was an escape.

00:22:09.800 --> 00:22:11.100
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: When you,

00:22:11.100 --> 00:22:14.940
also mentioned reading
about Puerto Rico.

00:22:14.940 --> 00:22:16.240
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: I did.

00:22:16.240 --> 00:22:18.550
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: But
not seeing people

00:22:18.550 --> 00:22:20.440
that looked like you in books.

00:22:20.440 --> 00:22:22.970
I remember when I first
saw myself in a book

00:22:22.970 --> 00:22:24.520
and what it meant to me.

00:22:24.520 --> 00:22:27.370
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR:
When I was little --

00:22:27.370 --> 00:22:29.910
first of all, my family had come

00:22:29.910 --> 00:22:36.600
from Puerto Rico during World
War II, I was born in 1954,

00:22:36.600 --> 00:22:40.210
many of them, my father
and my grandmother and most

00:22:40.210 --> 00:22:45.450
of my aunts included and uncles,
didn't yet speak English.

00:22:45.450 --> 00:22:47.420
So, I didn't have guidance

00:22:47.420 --> 00:22:50.650
on what I should be
reading in English.

00:22:50.650 --> 00:22:57.190
And because of that there may
have been books on biographies

00:22:57.190 --> 00:23:01.510
or biographies, but it wasn't
something I was exposed to.

00:23:01.510 --> 00:23:06.190
And because of that I didn't
have the opportunity to read

00:23:06.190 --> 00:23:09.580
about people who were like me.

00:23:09.580 --> 00:23:15.780
And I know now, because I
know there are so many books

00:23:15.780 --> 00:23:20.060
about people from so many
different backgrounds for kids,

00:23:20.060 --> 00:23:23.280
that they can see
themselves like you did.

00:23:23.280 --> 00:23:29.290
But we were a new migration
to the United States.

00:23:29.290 --> 00:23:31.410
Not new, because we've been
a part of the United States

00:23:31.410 --> 00:23:35.990
since 1988, but coming over
in significant numbers,

00:23:35.990 --> 00:23:40.130
Puerto Ricans didn't
start until the 1950s.

00:23:40.130 --> 00:23:44.980
And, so, as a result of that
there weren't a lot of books

00:23:44.980 --> 00:23:50.350
about people like me with curly
hair and who spoke Spanish.

00:23:50.350 --> 00:23:52.030
Now there are.

00:23:52.030 --> 00:23:54.110
And you can meet one of them --

00:23:54.110 --> 00:23:55.410
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: In this book.

00:23:55.410 --> 00:23:56.710
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: In my translation.

00:23:56.710 --> 00:23:58.510
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: I have it --

00:23:58.510 --> 00:24:02.730
[ Applause ]

00:24:02.730 --> 00:24:04.570
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: "Pasando Paginas."

00:24:04.570 --> 00:24:06.190
It's very important to me

00:24:06.190 --> 00:24:10.510
that everything I write be
translated into Spanish.

00:24:10.510 --> 00:24:16.320
[ Applause ]

00:24:16.320 --> 00:24:18.790
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: And
published simultaneously.

00:24:18.790 --> 00:24:20.090
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR: Yes.

00:24:20.090 --> 00:24:23.570
Now the middle school book we're
a little behind, but I'm told

00:24:23.570 --> 00:24:24.870
in a couple of months
we're going

00:24:24.870 --> 00:24:26.170
to have the Spanish version.

00:24:26.170 --> 00:24:27.470
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: Right, yeah.

00:24:27.470 --> 00:24:29.970
But to have the picture book
come out in both languages

00:24:29.970 --> 00:24:31.270
at the same time is important.

00:24:31.270 --> 00:24:32.570
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR:
Very important to me.

00:24:32.570 --> 00:24:34.270
I can give you a
secret, for those of you

00:24:34.270 --> 00:24:35.820
who are teaching yourselves

00:24:35.820 --> 00:24:39.590
or your kids Spanish,
buy both versions.

00:24:39.590 --> 00:24:41.930
They can read them side by side.

00:24:46.240 --> 00:24:47.620
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: You're
a librarian in hiding.

00:24:47.620 --> 00:24:48.920
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: Carla,

00:24:48.920 --> 00:24:51.400
you know that I get very
tired of sitting down.

00:24:51.400 --> 00:24:52.700
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: Well.

00:24:52.700 --> 00:24:54.000
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: Right, I know.

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:55.820
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: We have a treat

00:24:55.820 --> 00:24:59.950
and I had the wonderful
experience of being part

00:24:59.950 --> 00:25:04.260
of your first book tour
when I was in Baltimore.

00:25:04.260 --> 00:25:10.920
And you said, "You know, I
get a little feisty and I want

00:25:10.920 --> 00:25:13.750
to be out with people."

00:25:13.750 --> 00:25:19.240
And the -- I guess I could
say, the security people

00:25:19.240 --> 00:25:25.710
that accompany you kind of
blanch when she does that.

00:25:25.710 --> 00:25:27.680
But that's what she's
going to do.

00:25:27.680 --> 00:25:28.980
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR:
That's what I'm going to do.

00:25:28.980 --> 00:25:30.280
[inaudible]

00:25:30.280 --> 00:25:31.580
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: Because
we're going to start

00:25:31.580 --> 00:25:32.880
with question and answers.

00:25:32.880 --> 00:25:34.180
And I forgot to say
that at the beginning,

00:25:34.180 --> 00:25:36.720
because I was kind of excited.

00:25:36.720 --> 00:25:40.070
We have questions from the
audience that you have filled

00:25:40.070 --> 00:25:45.280
out and I'm going to read them,
and, Justice, you wanted me

00:25:45.280 --> 00:25:48.370
to ask and say the names.

00:25:48.370 --> 00:25:53.270
Oh, and the first one is Maria,
who is a 9 year old girl.

00:25:53.270 --> 00:25:54.570
And where is Maria?

00:25:54.570 --> 00:25:55.870
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR: Oh.

00:25:55.870 --> 00:25:58.760
Can I say one thing, Carla?

00:25:58.760 --> 00:26:00.550
I will walk around.

00:26:00.550 --> 00:26:03.420
It's not fair to all
those people back there

00:26:03.420 --> 00:26:04.860
that they can't see me.

00:26:04.860 --> 00:26:10.780
So, I'm going to go
say hello to people.

00:26:10.780 --> 00:26:12.890
You will see a lot of people

00:26:12.890 --> 00:26:14.230
with little things
in their ears.

00:26:14.230 --> 00:26:16.440
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: A lot.

00:26:16.440 --> 00:26:19.400
&gt;&gt; Justice Sonia
Sotomayor: A lot of them.

00:26:19.400 --> 00:26:22.830
They are here to
protect me from me.

00:26:24.170 --> 00:26:27.050
They don't like me doing
this, I do it anyway.

00:26:27.050 --> 00:26:28.350
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: She does it.

00:26:28.350 --> 00:26:29.650
I've seen it.

00:26:29.650 --> 00:26:30.950
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR: But,

00:26:30.950 --> 00:26:33.660
if you jump up unexpectedly,
they get scared.

00:26:33.660 --> 00:26:34.960
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN:
No, sudden moves.

00:26:34.960 --> 00:26:36.660
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR:
And if too many of you do it,

00:26:36.660 --> 00:26:38.530
they'll pull me back
onto the stage.

00:26:38.530 --> 00:26:39.920
I don't want that.

00:26:39.920 --> 00:26:42.180
So, stay seated please.

00:26:42.180 --> 00:26:46.940
But I'm going to walk and
whoever asks the question,

00:26:46.940 --> 00:26:49.380
would you raise your hand.

00:26:49.380 --> 00:26:52.800
And if you're little jump up
and down or come to the middle

00:26:52.800 --> 00:26:55.700
so we can see where
you are, okay?

00:26:55.700 --> 00:26:58.590
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: Okay, we're
going to start with Maria.

00:26:58.590 --> 00:27:02.300
Who's a 9 year old girl and
who wants to be president.

00:27:02.300 --> 00:27:04.100
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: Oh, wow.

00:27:04.100 --> 00:27:13.200
[ Applause ]

00:27:13.200 --> 00:27:16.340
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: And Maria wants
to know, what is your advice

00:27:16.340 --> 00:27:18.960
about what I should do now.

00:27:18.960 --> 00:27:20.260
Thank you, Maria Tarzere
[assumed spelling].

00:27:20.260 --> 00:27:22.410
At 9 years old.

00:27:22.410 --> 00:27:24.070
So, Maria, where are you, Maria.

00:27:24.070 --> 00:27:25.430
There she is.

00:27:25.430 --> 00:27:26.730
Oh.

00:27:26.730 --> 00:27:28.220
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: Oh, this side.

00:27:28.220 --> 00:27:30.970
All right, I'm coming down.

00:27:30.970 --> 00:27:32.440
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: I'm
going to stay here

00:27:32.440 --> 00:27:36.210
and the Justice is
going to see you.

00:27:36.210 --> 00:27:40.970
Oh, Maria, you are so
smart to ask this now.

00:27:40.970 --> 00:27:43.760
At 9. Because that's --

00:27:43.760 --> 00:27:45.060
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: Hola.

00:27:45.060 --> 00:27:46.370
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN:
It's never too early.

00:27:46.370 --> 00:27:47.670
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR:
will you give me a hug.

00:27:47.670 --> 00:27:48.970
Thank you.

00:27:48.970 --> 00:27:50.270
Thank you.

00:27:50.270 --> 00:27:52.070
Look at those guys.

00:27:52.070 --> 00:27:57.180
[ Applause ]

00:27:57.180 --> 00:27:59.670
Well, are you here --
who are you hear with?

00:27:59.670 --> 00:28:00.970
&gt;&gt; Maria: My mom and dad.

00:28:00.970 --> 00:28:02.270
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA SOTOMAYOR:

00:28:02.270 --> 00:28:03.570
Can we go back there
so I can meet them?

00:28:03.570 --> 00:28:05.870
All right, let's go take a walk.

00:28:07.180 --> 00:28:11.570
Now, Maria, I walk and talk.

00:28:11.570 --> 00:28:16.200
Thank you.

00:28:16.200 --> 00:28:20.580
I'm so proud of you
for having big dreams.

00:28:20.580 --> 00:28:26.930
That is so important, because,
you see, if you don't dream big,

00:28:26.930 --> 00:28:29.880
you can't become something big.

00:28:29.880 --> 00:28:34.760
You have to dream big to want
to work hard to get there.

00:28:34.760 --> 00:28:37.620
And you have to start
by studying,

00:28:37.620 --> 00:28:39.750
because anything you want

00:28:39.750 --> 00:28:44.780
to be requires hard
work and a lot of study.

00:28:44.780 --> 00:28:50.910
Nothing in life that you
do where you're successful,

00:28:50.910 --> 00:28:54.290
can you do without hard work.

00:28:54.290 --> 00:28:59.620
Even athletes, and a lot of
people think, "Oh, they just get

00:28:59.620 --> 00:29:02.230
up and throw that basketball."

00:29:02.230 --> 00:29:03.600
They don't do that.

00:29:03.600 --> 00:29:08.870
They practice and
practice and practice

00:29:08.870 --> 00:29:11.360
until they get really good.

00:29:11.360 --> 00:29:13.490
That's their study, practicing.

00:29:13.490 --> 00:29:16.360
But they also have to
read about basketball,

00:29:16.360 --> 00:29:19.540
they have to know how
to play it, so they have

00:29:19.540 --> 00:29:21.830
to read all these
things that tell them,

00:29:21.830 --> 00:29:24.740
how do I form this
line, how do I protect

00:29:24.740 --> 00:29:27.980
against somebody
getting passed me.

00:29:27.980 --> 00:29:30.520
That's what it will
be like in your life.

00:29:30.520 --> 00:29:34.180
So you have to read a lot
about a lot of things.

00:29:34.180 --> 00:29:37.510
Especially if you're president,
because you have to know --

00:29:37.510 --> 00:29:46.140
[ Applause ]

00:29:46.140 --> 00:29:53.810
You tell me where your
mom and dad are, okay?

00:29:53.810 --> 00:29:55.110
So, you know the
President not only has

00:29:55.110 --> 00:29:57.750
to know American
history, he has to know --

00:29:57.750 --> 00:30:01.520
all right, oh, you're here.

00:30:01.520 --> 00:30:04.420
Hello. I'm so proud of you.

00:30:04.420 --> 00:30:05.720
&gt;&gt; Jenny Gordon: It's
a pleasure to meet you.

00:30:05.720 --> 00:30:07.020
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: Hello, hello.

00:30:07.020 --> 00:30:08.320
&gt;&gt; Anthony Tarzere:
Hello, nice to meet you.

00:30:08.320 --> 00:30:09.620
&gt;&gt; Justice Sonia Sotomayor:
Tell me your names.

00:30:09.620 --> 00:30:10.920
&gt;&gt; Jenny Gordon:
I'm Jenny Gordon.

00:30:10.920 --> 00:30:12.220
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: Jenny.

00:30:12.220 --> 00:30:13.520
&gt;&gt; Anthony Tarzere:
Anthony Tarzere.

00:30:13.520 --> 00:30:14.820
&gt;&gt; JUSTICE SONIA
SOTOMAYOR: Hello.

